BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Beatrice | Ruth Poor
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T090000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T160000
UID:2602176-LJDC9Fsk-P4iP04uqBBA
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/LWznMwws6U-NK01KN5n0gA.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:On view February 21 - March 18\, 2026\n\nOpening Reception Su
 nday\, February 22\, 2026\, 1-4 pm\n\nRuth L. Poor\, raised in Indiana\, u
 ses their work to dissect memories of the rural Midwest and to investigate
  intersections between power\, American history\, faith\, and deviancy. Po
 or received their MFA from the Painting & Drawing department at the School
  of the Art Institute of Chicago \\(SAIC\\) and completed their B.A. in St
 udio Art and Religious Studies at Cornell College and DePauw University. T
 hey currently reside in Chicago\, Illinois\, where they teach at SAIC\, No
 rth Central College\, and College of DuPage\, and teach/advise with the Pr
 ison \\+ Neighborhood Arts Project. They have shown work nationally and in
 ternationally at venues such as the University ofChicago \\[Chicago\, IL\\
 ]\, Secrist|Beach Gallery \\[Chicago\, IL\\]\, the New York Academy of Art
  \\[New York\, NY\\]\, Zolla/Lieberman Gallery\\[Chicago\, IL\\]\, Art EXP
 O \\[Chicago\, IL\\]\, The Green Gallery \\[Milwaukee\, WI\\]\, ADDS DONNA
  Gallery \\[Chicago\, IL\\]\, Manifest Gallery\\[Cincinnati\, OH\\]\, Woma
 n Made Gallery \\[Chicago\, IL\\]\, and Indiana University \\[Bloomington\
 , IN\\]. They are also a current Artist-in-Residence with the Chicago Arti
 st Coalition \\(2024-2026\\).
LOCATION:Evanston Art Center
URL:https://www.evanstonartcenter.org/exhibitions/woundwomb-ruth-poor
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:In Paper & Shadow | Sarah Nguyen
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T090000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T160000
UID:2602172Pzdjbjhjkixh7zqucJMrA
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/JJnNSEYEwU2DmpYheCN85Q.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:On View February 21 - March 15\, 2026\n\nOpening Reception Sun
 day\, February 22nd\, 1-4 pm\n\nSarah Nguyen is a mixed media artist\, wo
 rking primarily with paper. Storytelling is central to her hand-cut fiber 
 panels and paintings. Her work has appeared in numerous national and inter
 national solo and group exhibitions and publications. Her work has been pa
 rt of exhibitions in museums and festivals\, including \\(but not limited 
 to\\) Seattle’s Wing Luke Museum of Asian Pacific Experience\, the Daum 
 Museum\, Pyramid Hill Sculpture Grounds and Museum\, the Truman Museum\, C
 heekwood Estates & Gardens\, and Kansas City’s 2018 Open Spaces. She has
  taken part in a number of artist residencies from around the world as a v
 isiting artist and teacher\, including Serbia\, Bulgaria\, Japan\, and Fra
 nce\, as well as the United States.\n\nSarah received her BFA in Illustrat
 ion from Rhode Island School of Design and her MFA in Painting from the Un
 iversity of the Arts in Philadelphia.
LOCATION:Evanston Art Center
URL:https://www.evanstonartcenter.org/exhibitions/paper-shadow-sarah-nguye
 n
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Changing Channels
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T150000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T170000
UID:260214JFwssTN1Lk2YAi2S66jhjg
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/ZDlegA-GyESas6dLJp6Bbw.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Based on actual events\, CHANGING CHANNELS is set backstage 
 at the DuMont Television Network in New York City in 1952. It is the peak 
 of the “Red Scare\,” and 151 actors\, authors\, and journalists are pu
 t on the Red Channels list\, with alleged ties to communism. As Cold War h
 ysteria sweeps the nation\, actress Maggie Carlin finds herself accused ju
 st as her hit comedy show is taking off.
LOCATION:City Lit Theater
URL:https://cityspark.com/calendar/#!/show?location=Evanston,+IL&distance=
 5#/details/changing-channels/18024385/2026-03-15T15
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Unveiling Evanston Women Artists
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T130000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T160000
UID:260212qdbhmyJZ1Ei0h_5EnId44w
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/CT7F4yijQ0aXrT9eldBcGg.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Women artists have historically remained in relative obscurity
  due to several factors including societal pressures prioritizing domestic
 ity and systemic exclusion. This exhibit showcases women artists from our 
 collection of 20th century art and seeks to open the door to many more und
 errepresented Evanston women artists. Exhibit opens February 14 and runs t
 hrough April 12\, 2026.
LOCATION:Evanston History Center
URL:https://cityspark.com/calendar/#!/show?location=Evanston,+IL&distance=
 5#/details/unveiling-evanston-women-artists/17988797/2026-03-15T13
X-SOURCE:CitySpark Evanston
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:The Factory Theater Presents "Kubrickian\," Feb. 13 - Mar. 15
DTSTART;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T150000
DTEND;TZID=CDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T150000
UID:260118CRlNTkwyE0uecJ6wZpmr6A
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://citysparkstorage.blob.core.windows.net/p
 ortalimages/portalimages/oA6shNHiIUC7Oj3v3yuaZw.large.jpg
DESCRIPTION:The Factory Theater\, 1623 W. Howard St.\, is proud to present
  Kubrickian\, February 20 - March 15\, written by Zack Peercy and directed
  by AJ Schwartz. \n\nTrapped in a white space\, three men who should be fo
 cused on escape or explanation can’t seem to stop talking about acclaime
 d film director Stanley Kubrick. This trippy existential show is a hauntin
 g and hilarious look at masculinity\, creativity\, and capitalism.\n\nThe 
 regular performance schedule is Fridays and Saturdays at 8 p.m. Sundays at
  3 p.m. The Tickets are $30 and may be purchased through the box office by
  calling 312-275-5757 or by visiting TheFactoryTheater.com.
